title: Country diary: An autumn fireball that’s a sanctuary for insects | Kate Blincoe
summary: In Caistor St Edmund, Norfolk, the rare Robin's pincushion has garnered attention for its unique and intriguing name. This peculiar growth, often found on wild roses, is a type of gall created by gall wasps. Its unusual appearance and origin make it a fascinating subject for nature enthusiasts.
